So what made Hazel’s pumpkin pie leave such an impression on me, even after all these years?  Sure, you could assume that it was just the fact that my Granny, one of the women who taught me to bake and a person I love with all my heart, made the cake and I would of course love it out of my sheer emotional connection to the baker.   That is not the case.  Her pies really focused on the pumpkin.  So many times a pumpkin pie is loaded up with spices that the subtle, fresh flavor of the pumpkin is lost and it ends up tasting like a cinnamon pie with a dash of clove, nutmeg and ginger.  Granny’s pies were simple and delicious.  There was a nice balance of nutmeg, ginger and cinnamon.  She went a bit heavier on the clove, which I love.  I also remember eating her pumpkin pie and not feeling the need to cover it in whipped cream, although I have to admit (and I say this knowing I may be a bit judged) that there were times that I added a hefty dollop of cool-whip.

&nbsp;

Today, we pay homage to this lovely, feisty, Texas lady with the flavor Hazel’s Pumpkin Pie.  We buy Texas pie pumpkins and roast them in the oven in our very own kitchen.  Once the seeds and flesh have been removed, pounds of it are blended into our ice cream base and enhanced with a little nutmeg, ginger and cinnamon.  We go a bit heavy on the clove.  What we get is the best pumpkin ice cream I’ve ever had that tastes like the most delicious, freshest pumpkin pie I’ve ever eaten.  Actually, if you’ve never had the pleasure of eating my Granny’s pumpkin pie, it’s probably better.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: right;">- Anthony Sobotik, co-founder &amp; chef</p>
&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1704" alt="3-pumpkinpie" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/3-pumpkinpie.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1704" />

There really is a Hazel and she’s my granny.  Each year for Thanksgiving she would make at least one pumpkin pie and she’d say it was just for me, usually by whispering it in my ear.  Maybe she didn’t want the other grandchildren to hear.  Whatever the reason, I LOVE her pumpkin pie.  I remember seeing them lined up with the other desserts on my grandparents’ bar and going out of my mind counting the minutes until it was time to dive in.  I’m a huge baked goods fanatic and even among all the other offerings my family members had crafted, my main objective was to get a piece of her pumpkin pie on my plate before it had been devoured by my cousins.

&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1703" alt="3-grannyhazel" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/3-grannyhazel.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1703" />

