It's a mess outside, guys!  It's gloomy, 50 degrees, and raining as I write, hiding in a windowless room, eating countless spoonfuls of ice cream.  Good news for y'all is that it's probably 70 degrees and sunny as you read this.  Or if it isn't, it probably will be in a couple of days.<!--more-->

&nbsp;

This is Texas in November, folks.  There are cold fronts, rain, and sometimes (rarely) ice, but if you give it a couple of days, the sun always returns to warm you back up.  That's why I fled the Northeast as soon as I could.  I outright cannot tolerate cold... except for cold ice cream.

&nbsp;

It's a little bit ironic, but I love ice cream MOST in the winter.

&nbsp;
<div><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1721" alt="5-snack" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/5-snack.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1721" /></div>
&nbsp;

Ice cream serves a very special purpose in the winter.  It's an indulgent, belly-warming, sweet, and satisfying treat for the end of every dark winter day.  It's the best feel-good food.  Straight out of a pint with a really big spoon, scooped onto a warm slice of pecan pie, or floating in a tall glass of dark beer, ice cream seems to round out every dish, every meal, every day.

&nbsp;

I crave warm, rich foods &amp; drinks in cold weather.  Pie, cobbler, brownies, coffee, tea, hot chocolate.  With ice cream.  Have you ever had a scoop of vanilla ice cream in your coffee?  It's better than any coffee creamer.  In hot chocolate, it's better than marshmallows.  With a pint readily available in the freezer, you might find yourself savoring your ice cream straight out of the pint for hours because it takes so much longer to melt in the cold.  I've been nursing this still-frozen pint on my desk for an hour ... as if there aren't already enough reasons to love ice cream in this weather.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: right;">- Diana Vassar, Kitchen Manager</p>

<div style="text-align: right;"></div>
<div style="text-align: right;"></div>
