<div><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1722" alt="4-hotchocolate" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/4-hotchocolate.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1722" /></div>

Everyone likes an old fashioned campfire s’more.

<!--more-->

Yes, the chocolate is usually cold and hard and, yes, if you’re anything like me you sometimes impatiently but accidentally force your marshmallow so deep into the campfire that it bursts into flames.  But it’s all cool because that’s what s’mores are about.  Camping, fires, junk food, sleeping (or not sleeping), bugs, grass, dirt, and a sky full of stars.  Oh, and s’mores.  Always s’mores.

&nbsp;

We like s’mores a LOT.  Where I’m from, s’more time is in the summertime.  But according to Anthony, s’more weather is cold weather in Texas.  We agree to disagree.

&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1741" alt="5-smoreingredients" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/5-smoreingredients.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1741" />

&nbsp;

No matter the time of year, we like cold, hard chunks of chocolate and melted (sometimes burnt) marshmallows cozily stacked between two cinnamon and honey graham crackers.  Our S’more Meringue ice cream captures all of that.  We flavor the ice cream with Austin Honey Company honey, cinnamon, and molasses (it tastes just like a graham cracker) and then sprinkle in some shattered bits of dark Great Bean chocolate.

&nbsp;

It’s the thick swirl of torched meringue that makes our s’more a S’more Meringue.  Our made-in-house pillow-y soft meringue tastes just like the burnt edges and ooey gooey center of melted marshmallows.  And quite honestly, it’s perfect.

&nbsp;

We don’t camp much around here, but we really don't need to when we have S’more Meringue ice cream in our freezer.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: right;">- Diana Vassar, Kitchen Manager</p>
&nbsp;

