<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1748" alt="5-smore" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/5-smore.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1748" />

I get asked all the time how we come up with new flavors.  They’re usually the result of what’s in season in Texas or derived from a recipe to which I have a personal attachment.  Because of this, our flavors are a true representation of the flavors and culture of Texas.  <!--more-->

&nbsp;

However, I often fail to mention the third source of flavor inspiration:  flavors crafted for special events.  Luckily, Austin is a city with no shortage of events throughout the year.  Each time we partner with a new event, we look at it as an opportunity to create a completely new flavor or re-examine one that we’ve been kicking around the kitchen.  They also serve as an excellent way for us to get feedback on something that hasn’t been in one of our shops.  Over the years we’ve created, floats, ice cream sandwiches and many custom flavors for special events that have ended up on the menu.

&nbsp;

Just recently we were asked to participate in the Big Reds and Bubbles event at the historic Driskill Hotel.  Being that the event was centered around an extensive wine tasting, we decided to create a flavor that celebrated that.  For some time, I’d been longing to create a flavor that was in some part crafted using a local wine.  More recently, my focus had been on incorporating the wine into a cake that could be featured in our ice cream.  This event seemed like the perfect opportunity to see this notion to fruition.

&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1759" alt="6-beckerwine" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/11/6-beckerwine.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1759" />

&nbsp;

First we decided on the cake.  There was some talk of a white or yellow cake but I was dead set on chocolate.  So chocolate it was.  Next we selected the wine.  Personally, I’m not a fan of merlots in general so I knew I wanted to stir clear of that varietal.  I landed on a cabernet sauvignon from one of my favorite vineyards in the Texas Hill Country; Becker Vineyards.  The combination of the wine with the delicious cake that Diana created was right on.  Not wanting to take away from the varied notes of the wine cake, the base was a vanilla bean cream cheese.

&nbsp;

Cabernet Cake and Cream, as we call it, was very well received at the event and everyone was asking ‘How did you come up with this flavor’ and ‘When will it be in your shops?’.  Now  you know the how and it looks like the when will be this coming Valentine’s Day.

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: right;">- Anthony Sobotik, chef &amp; co-owner</p>
