We are so excited to finally introduce one of our favorite frothy beverages to our ice cream repertoire.  Hooray for beer!

<!--more-->

&nbsp;

As with most of our flavors, we dwelled on an idea for a beer ice cream for as long as I can remember.  There’s a lot of good beer in Texas.  We love beer.  And as you might imagine, good beer is great with good ice cream.

&nbsp;

Scotch Ales are quickly becoming one of my favorite types of beer.  They feature a malt-dominant profile, very low bitterness, and higher than average alcohol content.  In other words, they’re bubbly, slightly sweet, full bodied brews that are so dangerously smooth they’ll knock you off your feet.  Their warm flavor makes them perfect for the holidays.  Their minimal hop presence and low bitterness also make them perfect for ice cream – a Scotch Ale can be reduced without becoming unpalatably bitter (try cooking any IPA down to syrup and you’ll see what I mean).

&nbsp;

<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-1818" alt="8-keg" src="http://ilikelick.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/8-keg.jpg" width="440" height="282" data-id="1818" />

&nbsp;

We get our Scotch Ale from Guadalupe Brewing Company in New Braunfels, just a stone’s throw away from Austin.  It’s a little bit smoky, sweet, malty, and aged in American oak.  It’s unique, yet balanced, and we love it.

&nbsp;

Not only does this beer make a fine ice cream, but it also makes a mean gingerbread.  Made with loads of zingy fresh ginger, cinnamon, molasses, and a frothy glass of Guadalupe Brewing Company’s Scotch Ale, this gingerbread’s got a punch.  I highly recommend picking up a pint of ice cream to eat and a pint of Scotch Ale to wash it down for the holidays.  The flavors go so well together.  They make me holiday happy (and I’m not just saying that because I made it, I swear!).

&nbsp;
<p style="text-align: right;">- Diana Vassar, Kitchen Manager</p>
<p style="text-align: right;"></p>
